  "response_text": "Here is a 3-day meal plan designed for a student to improve iron levels. It focuses on **heme iron** (from animal sources, which is easily absorbed) and **non-heme iron** (from plants) paired with **Vitamin C** to boost absorption.\n\n**Key Tips for this Plan:**\n- **Vitamin C is your best friend:** Always pair iron-rich plant foods with Vitamin C (citrus, bell peppers, broccoli, tomatoes).\n- **Avoid tea/coffee with meals:** Tannins in tea and coffee block iron absorption. Drink them between meals (e.g., 1 hour before or 2 hours after).\n- **Cook in a cast-iron pan:** This can leach small amounts of iron into your food, especially acidic foods like tomato sauce.\n\n---\n\n### Day 1: Boost & Build\n\n**Breakfast (Iron + Vitamin C combo)**\n- **Oatmeal** made with milk or fortified plant milk (check label for iron).\n- Stir in **2 tbsp pumpkin seeds** (good iron source).\n- Top with **strawberries or kiwi** (Vitamin C).\n- *Drink:* A small glass of orange juice.\n\n**Lunch (Heme Iron + Veggies)**\n- **Turkey and spinach wrap:** Whole wheat tortilla, 3-4 slices of lean turkey, handful of fresh spinach, sliced bell peppers (Vitamin C), and hummus.\n- **Side:** A handful of cherry tomatoes.\n- *Snack:* Apple slices (Vitamin C helps with later meals).\n\n**Dinner (High Heme Iron)**\n- **Beef stir-fry:** Small portion of lean beef strips (very high in heme iron) with broccoli, red bell peppers, and snap peas. Use a sauce made of low-sodium soy sauce, garlic, and ginger.\n- Serve over a small portion of **brown rice**.\n- *Tip:* Squeeze lime juice over the stir-fry for extra Vitamin C.\n\n**Evening Snack (if hungry)**\n- **Handful of dried apricots** (non-heme iron) and a few almonds.\n\n---\n\n### Day 2: Plant-Powered Iron\n\n**Breakfast (Iron + Vitamin C)**\n- **Scrambled eggs** (heme iron) with a handful of **chopped spinach** and **mushrooms**.\n- **Side:** Half a grapefruit (Vitamin C).\n- *Drink:* Water or milk.\n\n**Lunch (Lentil Power)**\n- **Lentil soup** (lentils are an iron powerhouse) made with tomatoes (Vitamin C), carrots, and celery.\n- **Side:** Whole grain bread or crackers.\n- *Snack:* **Hummus** with raw **broccoli florets** or **red pepper strips** (Vitamin C).\n\n**Dinner (Seafood Iron)**\n- **Canned sardines or mackerel** on whole wheat toast (sardines are very high in heme iron and cheap).\n- **Side:** A large **side salad** with spinach, bell peppers, and a lemon vinaigrette (Vitamin C).\n- *Tip:* If you don't like fish, swap for a **bean and quinoa bowl** (see Day 3 lunch style).\n\n**Evening Snack**\n- **A small square of dark chocolate** (70%+ cocoa – contains iron).\n\n---\n\n### Day 3: Mix & Match\n\n**Breakfast (Quick & Easy)**\n- **Fortified breakfast cereal** (e.g., Total, Cheerios, or Bran Flakes – check label for 100% DV iron).\n- **Top with** **sliced strawberries** (Vitamin C) and **milk**.\n- *Drink:* Water or milk.\n\n**Lunch (Bean & Grain Bowl)**\n- **Quinoa and black bean bowl:** Mix cooked quinoa (good iron) with black beans (excellent iron), corn, diced tomatoes, and avocado.\n- **Dressing:** Lime juice and cilantro (Vitamin C).\n- *Snack:* **Edamame** (soybeans) pods – a great iron-rich snack.\n\n**Dinner (Chicken & Greens)**\n- **Grilled chicken thigh** (contains more iron than breast) with a **sweet potato** (baked) and **steamed kale or collard greens** (very high in non-heme iron).\n- *Tip:* Squeeze lemon juice over the greens to boost iron absorption.\n- **Optional:** Add a side of **sautéed mushrooms**.\n\n**Evening Snack**\n- **A handful of raisins or dried mulberries** (both contain iron).\n\n---\n\n### Shopping List (Student Budget-Friendly)\n\n**Produce:**\n- Spinach (fresh or frozen)\n- Broccoli\n- Bell peppers (red/yellow)\n- Lemons & limes\n- Oranges or grapefruit\n- Strawberries or kiwi\n- Tomatoes (canned or fresh)\n- Avocado\n- Garlic, ginger, onion\n- Sweet potato\n\n**Proteins:**\n- Lean beef strips (buy in bulk, freeze portions)\n- Chicken thighs\n- Canned sardines or mackerel (very cheap)\n- Eggs\n- Turkey slices (deli)\n\n**Pantry / Canned:**\n- Canned lentils or dried lentils\n- Canned black beans\n- Quinoa\n- Brown rice\n- Fortified breakfast cereal\n- Dried apricots\n- Pumpkin seeds\n- Hummus\n- Dark chocolate (70%+)\n- Oatmeal\n\n**Dairy / Alternatives:**\n- Milk or fortified plant milk\n- Yogurt (optional – calcium can interfere, so eat separately from iron meals)\n\n### Final Advice for a Student:\n- **Prep ahead:** Cook a batch of quinoa, lentils, or brown rice at the start of the week.\n- **Frozen veggies:** Frozen spinach and broccoli are just as nutritious and cheaper.\n- **Take Vitamin C supplements?** Even a 250mg Vitamin C tablet taken with a meal can triple non-heme iron absorption.\n- **Don't overdo calcium:** Avoid taking calcium supplements or drinking milk at the same meal as your high-iron foods.\n\nLet me know if you have any dietary restrictions (vegetarian, vegan, allergies) and I can adjust the plan further!",
